Naivasha residents have expressed outrage over poor drainage that causes perennial flooding when it rains. They said pipes are clogged and effluent flows on the surface. The residents accused county officers of failing to demolish structures around waterways as ordered by Governor Lee Kinyanjui four months ago. They urged the county chief to follow up and ensure his directive is respected. The residents said Kihoto estate traders suffer huge losses as flooding is the new norm and roads are impassable. Naivasha Professional Association chairman Eskimos Kobia said the problem was getting worse by the day He said transport is frequently disrupted. “The directive by the governor to demolish all structures on waterways was met with support, but we’re concerned that this wasn’t enforced,” he said. Click here for the latest political news